Shopify is the default answer when someone says "I want to sell products online." And for good reason — it's polished, well-known, and you can have a store running in a day. But "running" and "running well" are different things, and the $39/month price tag on the website is not the number you'll actually pay.

Let me break down the real cost, because there's a specific point where Shopify stops being the smart choice and starts being an expensive habit.

## The sticker price vs. the real price

Shopify's Basic plan is $39/month. Here's what it includes: a storefront, a checkout, basic analytics, and the ability to list unlimited products. Sounds complete. Then you start building your store and realize you need:

### The apps you'll actually install

- **Product reviews** (Loox, Judge.me): $10-$25/month
- **Email marketing** (Klaviyo, Shopify Email): $0-$30/month depending on list size
- **Search and filtering** (Searchanise, Product Filter): $10-$20/month
- **Abandoned cart recovery** (beyond basic): $15-$30/month
- **SEO tools** (SEO Manager, Plug in SEO): $15-$25/month
- **Upselling/cross-selling** (Bold, ReConvert): $10-$30/month
- **Loyalty/rewards**: $20-$50/month
- **Custom fields/options** (for product customization): $10-$20/month

A typical Shopify store runs 5-8 paid apps. At the conservative end, that's $100/month in apps. At the higher end, $200/month. Plus Shopify's plan fee, you're looking at $139-$239/month.

### The annual and 2-year reality

| Cost | Monthly | Year 1 | Year 2 | 2-Year Total |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Shopify Basic | $39 | $468 | $468 | $936 |
| Apps (conservative) | $100 | $1,200 | $1,200 | $2,400 |
| Apps (moderate) | $175 | $2,100 | $2,100 | $4,200 |
| **Total (conservative)** | **$139** | **$1,668** | **$1,668** | **$3,336** |
| **Total (moderate)** | **$214** | **$2,568** | **$2,568** | **$5,136** |

And that's before the theme. Free Shopify themes are functional but generic. A premium theme runs $180-$380 one time. A custom Shopify theme from a developer: $2,000-$10,000.

## What a custom store costs

Our Store tier starts at $3,500 for a fully custom e-commerce site. That includes:

- Product catalog with search and filtering
- Secure checkout with Stripe
- Review collection
- Email capture and abandoned cart emails
- SEO-optimized product and category pages
- Mobile-first responsive design
- No monthly platform fees (just hosting, which we include in retainers)

The 2-year comparison:

| | Shopify (moderate apps) | Custom Store |
|---|---|---|
| Year 1 | $2,568 | $3,500 (build) |
| Year 2 | $2,568 | $0 (or $150/mo retainer = $1,800) |
| **2-Year Total** | **$5,136** | **$3,500-$5,300** |
| Year 3 | $2,568 | $1,800 (retainer) |
| **3-Year Total** | **$7,704** | **$5,300-$7,100** |

By year 2, they're roughly equal. By year 3, the custom store is cheaper. And the gap widens every year after that.

## When Shopify IS the right choice

I'm not here to tell you Shopify is bad. For certain businesses, it's genuinely the best option:

### High-volume stores (100+ products, thousands of orders/month)

If you're processing 500+ orders a month, Shopify's infrastructure earns its fee. Their checkout is battle-tested at scale, their inventory management handles complexity well, and their app ecosystem lets you bolt on specialized tools (multi-warehouse shipping, subscription management, wholesale portals) that would cost a fortune to custom-build.

### Businesses that need the app ecosystem

If your business model depends on specific integrations — say, print-on-demand with Printful, dropshipping with Oberlo, or subscription boxes with Recharge — Shopify's app marketplace is genuinely valuable. These integrations are plug-and-play on Shopify and would require custom development otherwise.

### Quick launches with uncertain product-market fit

Testing whether people will buy your product? Shopify gets you live in a day. A custom store takes 2-4 weeks. If you're not sure your product will sell, spending $3,500 before validation is risky. Start with Shopify, validate demand, then migrate to custom when you've proven the concept.

## When a custom store is the better move

### Under 50 products

This is the sweet spot for custom. If you're selling 10-50 products — a curated collection, a specialty food line, handmade goods, a local retail shop's online extension — you don't need Shopify's infrastructure. You need a fast, beautiful store that reflects your brand and doesn't nickel-and-dime you with app fees.

We built Peach & Thread Boutique's online store as a custom site. It loads faster than Shopify, the design matches their physical shop's aesthetic perfectly, and they're not paying $150/month in app fees for features that are baked into their site.

### When brand matters more than features

Shopify stores tend to look like Shopify stores. Even with a premium theme, there's a sameness to the layout, the cart drawer, the collection pages. If your brand is your competitive advantage — artisan products, luxury goods, anything where presentation is part of the value — a custom store lets you control every pixel.

### When you want to own your platform

Same argument as website builders: on Shopify, your store lives on Shopify's servers, in Shopify's format. If you leave, you can export product data (CSVs), but your design, your URL structure, your checkout customizations — those stay behind. A custom store is yours. You can host it anywhere, hand it to any developer, or modify it without asking permission.

## The product count framework

Here's the simplest way to decide:

**Under 20 products**: Custom store, almost always. Shopify is overkill and overpriced for a small catalog. Your build cost will be lower, and you'll save every month.

**20-50 products**: Custom store for most businesses. The exception: if you need complex inventory management (variants, multi-location stock) or specific app integrations.

**50-200 products**: Could go either way. If the products are straightforward (no complex variants, no subscriptions), custom is still viable and cheaper long-term. If you need heavy automation, Shopify starts earning its fee.

**200+ products**: Shopify or a dedicated e-commerce platform. At this scale, the infrastructure and tooling justify the monthly cost.

## One more thing: transaction fees

Shopify charges 2% on every transaction if you don't use Shopify Payments (their built-in processor). If you use Shopify Payments, that drops to 0% — but Shopify Payments charges 2.9% + $0.30, which is the same as Stripe. On a custom store with Stripe, you pay the same 2.9% + $0.30 processing fee and nothing else. No platform percentage on top.

On a store doing $10,000/month in sales, that 2% Shopify surcharge (if you use an external processor) is $200/month — $2,400/year — just in extra fees.

## The bottom line

Shopify is a good product that makes sense for some businesses. But for the 80% of small businesses selling under 50 products, it's more platform than you need at a price that compounds painfully over time. A custom store costs more upfront but less every year after, and you own it completely.

Run the numbers for your situation. If you're spending more than $150/month on Shopify + apps for a catalog under 50 products, there's a better option.

